  "prompt": "How do QR codes work?",
  "response": "QR (Quick Response) codes work through the following key principles:\n\n1. Structure\n- A matrix of black and white squares\n- Contains data in a two-dimensional format\n- Can store more information than traditional barcodes\n\n2. Encoding\n- Data is converted into binary (0s and 1s)\n- Squares represent these binary values\n- Three distinctive squares in the corners help scanners orient the code\n\n3. Scanning Process\n- Camera or scanner reads the pattern of squares\n- Interprets black and white squares as binary data\n- Software decodes the binary information into text, URLs, contact info, etc.\n\n4. Data Types\n- Can store various types of data:\n  - Website URLs\n  - Contact information\n  - Plain text\n  - Wi-Fi login credentials\n  - Payment information\n\n5. Error Correction\n- Built-in redundancy allows code to be readable even if partially damaged\n- Different levels of error correction available\n\n6. Technical Details\n- Uses Reed-Solomon error correction algorithm\n- Can store up to 4,296 alphanumeric characters\n- Can be quickly scanned from any angle\n\nModern smartphones can typically scan QR codes directly through their camera apps, making them very convenient for quick information transfer.",
